      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        The Property Manager's Role When Selling a Tenanted Property in Brisbane 2026
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Selling with a tenant in place adds a layer of coordination that many landlords underestimate. Here's what your property manager needs to do and how to set the campaign up for a smooth result.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling an investment property in Brisbane while it is tenanted is a common scenario, but one where the coordination between your property manager, your selling agent, and the tenant needs to be managed carefully from the start. The legal framework governing tenant rights in Queensland is specific about notice periods, access frequency, and the conditions under which entry is permitted. Getting this wrong creates friction during your campaign and, in some cases, can affect your sale result.</p>

      <p>This article focuses on the property manager's role specifically: what they need to do before the campaign, during it, and after a contract is signed. If you are selling a tenanted property and want a broader overview of your obligations as a landlord and seller, see our <a href="/insights/selling-tenanted-property-queensland" style="color:#f5d07a;">guide to selling a tenanted property in Queensland</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Before the campaign: what the property manager needs to do first</h2>
      <p>The property manager should be the first person you contact when you decide to sell. They hold the lease documentation, know the tenant, and are the person who will need to give notice and manage access for the duration of the campaign. Starting the process without looping them in immediately creates unnecessary complications.</p>

      <p>The first step is a review of the lease. The property manager needs to confirm whether the tenant is on a fixed-term lease or a periodic tenancy, and when the lease expires or can be brought to an end. This directly affects your options as a seller:</p>

      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li>If the tenant is on a periodic tenancy, you can end the tenancy with the required notice once a contract is signed, or negotiate an earlier end by agreement.</li>
        <li>If the tenant is on a fixed-term lease, the lease runs with the property. A new owner takes the property subject to the existing lease and cannot end it early without mutual agreement.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>This matters because it affects your buyer pool. Owner-occupier buyers typically want possession at settlement, which is not possible if a fixed-term lease extends beyond that date. A good property manager should be able to tell you clearly what your options are and whether negotiating an early end to the lease with the tenant is worth pursuing before you list.</p>

      <p>The property manager should also conduct a routine inspection before the campaign begins. Knowing the current condition of the property and addressing any maintenance issues before photography and open homes is important. A tenant living in a property they know is for sale may not have maintained it to the standard it needs to be presented at.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tenant communication: getting it right from the start</h2>
      <p>The tenant's cooperation during the campaign is not guaranteed, but it is enormously valuable. A tenant who allows reasonable access, keeps the property tidy for open homes, and does not make inspections difficult for buyers is a significant asset to the campaign. A tenant who is uncooperative, who allows the property to be in poor condition during open homes, or who makes access difficult is a material risk.</p>

      <p>The property manager's role here is to establish a clear, respectful communication channel with the tenant from the moment the decision to sell is made. This means:</p>

      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li>Formally notifying the tenant in writing that the property is going to market, using the correct legislative notice</li>
        <li>Explaining clearly what to expect during the campaign: the frequency of open homes, how notice will be provided, and what is required of them</li>
        <li>Discussing whether any incentive, such as a rent reduction during the campaign, would be appropriate in exchange for the tenant's cooperation and flexibility</li>
        <li>Answering any questions the tenant has about their rights and what happens to the lease if the property is sold</li>
      </ul>

      <p>A tenant who understands the process and feels treated fairly is far more likely to present the property well than one who feels blindsided or uninformed. This is a property manager responsibility, not a selling agent one.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">During the campaign: notice requirements and access logistics</h2>
      <p>Under the Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008, the property manager must give the tenant at least 24 hours' written notice before each entry for the purpose of showing the property to prospective buyers. The notice must specify the date, start time, and purpose of entry, and entry can only occur at a reasonable time.</p>

      <p>In practice this means that open home schedules cannot be set and changed freely without adequate notice to the tenant. The property manager must:</p>

      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li>Confirm each open home time with the tenant at least 24 hours in advance</li>
        <li>Ensure all access entries are documented in writing</li>
        <li>Coordinate with the selling agent on scheduling so that changes or additions to the inspection schedule are flagged in time</li>
        <li>Manage any private buyer inspections through the same notice process</li>
      </ul>

      <p>There is no legislative limit on the number of inspections during a sale campaign, but the property manager should use judgment here. Frequent inspections during short windows can become unreasonably disruptive to the tenant's enjoyment of the property, which creates legal risk and worsens the relationship. The property manager and selling agent should agree on a realistic inspection schedule before the campaign launches.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Photography and presentation</h2>
      <p>Photography for the listing requires access, and the property manager must give notice in the same way as for open homes. Before the photographer visits, the property manager should ideally conduct a pre-photography inspection or ask the tenant to ensure the property is presented to a reasonable standard.</p>

      <p>If the tenant's furniture and belongings will be in the photography, that is not necessarily a problem. Professionally staged photographs with neutral tenant furniture can present well. The issue arises when personal clutter, poor cleaning, or maintenance items that should have been resolved are visible in the listing photos. These cannot be easily fixed after the photos are taken.</p>

      <p>If the presentation risk is high, a conversation between the property manager and the tenant about expectations, including what areas of the property the photographer needs clear access to, is worth having before the shoot.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">After a contract: the property manager's role continues</h2>
      <p>Once a contract is signed, the property manager's work does not stop. The key tasks in the period between contract and settlement include:</p>

      <ul style="padding-left:1.5rem;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;">
        <li>If the new owner is an investor continuing the tenancy, coordinating the transfer of the property management agreement or facilitating the handover to a new managing agent if the buyer uses their own</li>
        <li>If the tenancy is ending at or before settlement, giving the tenant the correct termination notice under the Act and managing the bond claim process</li>
        <li>Facilitating the pre-settlement inspection, which the buyer is entitled to conduct under the contract to confirm the property's condition</li>
        <li>Collecting and transferring any outstanding rent to the settlement date</li>
        <li>Handing over all tenancy records, including the lease agreement, condition report, bond lodgement details, and maintenance history, to the new owner or their property manager</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to watch for</h2>
      <p>The most common problems in tenanted sales come from poor coordination between the property manager and the selling agent, last-minute notice failures that create access disputes with the tenant, and sellers who fail to involve the property manager early enough to manage the lease question properly before listing.</p>

      <p>If you are selling a tenanted Brisbane property and your property manager and selling agent have not had a direct conversation about the campaign, that is the first thing to fix. Both parties need to understand the access schedule, the notice obligations, and what the plan is for the tenancy after settlement before the campaign launches.</p>

